## 1. Missing global error handling

There's no error-handling middleware or process-level error capture. Unhandled errors in route handlers will either crash the process or leak stack traces.

```js
// At the end, AFTER all routes
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' });
});

app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err); // Use a real logger (pino/winston) in prod
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' ? 'Internal Server Error' : err.message,
  });
});

process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => { console.error('unhandledRejection', reason); });
process.on('uncaughtException', (err) => { console.error('uncaughtException', err); process.exit(1); });
```

Wrap async handlers so rejections reach the error middleware:
```js
const asyncHandler = (fn) => (req, res, next) => Promise.resolve(fn(req, res, next)).catch(next);
```

## 2. No input validation

Neither route currently takes input, but as soon as you add query params, path params, or a body, you need validation. Use a schema library rather than hand-rolled checks.

