## Issues Found

### 1. No global error handler
Express requires an explicit error-handling middleware; otherwise, uncaught errors leak stack traces to clients and can crash the process.

### 2. No `try/catch` or async error propagation
The current handlers are synchronous, but as soon as you add DB/fetch calls, unhandled promise rejections will silently fail. Use `express-async-errors` or wrap handlers.

### 3. No input validation on `/users` (or any route)
Even though `/users` doesn't currently accept input, there's no pattern established. Once query params or request bodies are added (pagination, filtering), unvalidated input becomes an injection vector.

### 4. No body parser limits
`express.json()` isn't configured, but when it's added, failing to set `limit` opens you to DoS via oversized payloads.

### 5. No security headers
Missing `helmet()` — leaves you exposed to clickjacking, MIME-sniffing, XSS reflection, etc.

### 6. No rate limiting
`/health` and `/users` can be hammered. Use `express-rate-limit`.

### 7. Leaking PII in `/users`
Real email addresses are returned with no auth/authorization check. Any caller receives full user records.

### 8. `console.log` instead of structured logging
Makes incident forensics hard. Use `pino` or `winston`.

### 9. No graceful shutdown
No `SIGTERM`/`SIGINT` handlers — in-flight requests get dropped on deploy.

### 10. Hardcoded port
`3000` should come from `process.env.PORT` (and be validated as an integer in a safe range).

